            <abstract>
                <p>According to <bibl>
                        <ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/>
                        <citedRange unit="page">20-21</citedRange>
                    </bibl>, at least three texts narrate the death of Emperor Julian the Apostate
                    through the involvement of <persName ref="PRS7025Mercury"/>. Two of these three
                    texts are presented in the form of miracles, known to have circulated along with
                        <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7292MartyrMa"/>, <ref type="work"
                        corresp="LIT7293MartyrMb"/>, and <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7294MartyrMc"
                    />, all of which are assigned to <date ref="ethiocal:Hedar25">the 25th of
                        Ḫǝdār</date>. These miracles were translated from the text contained in <ref
                        type="mss" corresp="BNFabb110"/> by <bibl>
                        <ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/>
                        <citedRange unit="page">22-24</citedRange>
                    </bibl> as the "First Miracle" and the "Second Miracle." This record pertains to
                    the "Second Miracle," here defined as the Miracle of Mercureos: Death of Emperor
                    Julian the Apostate (version b). This miracle is attested both with (<ref
                        type="mss" corresp="BNFabb110"/>) and without (<ref type="mss"
                        corresp="BNFabb92"/>) <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7304TammeraJulian"/>.
                </p>
